    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-05-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-05-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="761"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d761">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.91293/151</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extracts]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-05-09">May 9,
                            1929</date>.<lb/>[Received June 11.]</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 2083</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In reference to my telegrams No. 331, of April
                    30, 6 p.m., and No. 362, of May 8, 5 p.m.,<note n="65" xml:id="d761fn1">Latter
                        not printed.</note> concerning measures taken by the Nationalist Government
                    to bring about the removal from China of certain American correspondents whose
                    reporting has apparently proved distasteful to the Government, I have, the honor
                    to enclose a copy of a confidential memorandum supplied to me on May 2nd by Mr.
                    Hallett Abend, Peking correspondent of the <hi rend="italic">New York
                        Times</hi>,<note n="66" xml:id="d761fn2">Not printed.</note> in reference to
                    the Nationalist Government’s alleged efforts to control the foreign press.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <p>There is also enclosed copy of a note addressed to me on May 1st by Mr. D. C.
                        Bess,<note n="66" xml:id="d761fn3">Not printed.</note> United Press
                    representative in Peking, …</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <p>… From my dealings with the two correspondents named, I believe them to be
                    altogether trustworthy men, and consider that their confidential reports on the
                    foreign press situation in Shanghai deserve serious consideration.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">J. V. A. MacMurray</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
